21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34.102A-1 of Title 62, unless
24 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 17252 Page 2

1 A. Sections 1 through 5 of this act shall be known and may be
2 cited as the "Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund Act".
3 B. 1. The Legislature finds that Oklahoma’s long-term economic
4 growth and fiscal stability are best served by policies that promote
5 savings, investment, and reduced reliance on income taxation;
6 2. The Legislature further finds that states with an abundance
7 of energy resources that preserve and grow a portion of those
8 revenues through investments enjoy lower taxes and budget stability;
9 3. Establishing a sovereign wealth fund enables states to
10 convert public funds into a permanent financial asset that generates
11 long-term investment income for public purposes;
12 4. It is therefore the intent of the Legislature to create a
13 trust fund that produces a significant and sustainable revenue
14 stream, preserves and protects its principal, and over time,
15 provides taxpayer relief by replacing income tax revenue through the
16 power of recurring investment and compounding interest;
17 5. The trust fund should provide a means of conserving a
18 portion of the state’s revenues, especially driven by energy
19 resources, to benefit all generations of Oklahomans;
20 6. The trust fund should work in concert with efforts to reduce
21 and eliminate income tax;
22 7. The trust fund’s performance goal should seek market returns
23 during the fund’s growth phase lockout period; and
24
Req. No. 17252 Page 3

1 8. After the lockout phase, the trust fund’s performance goal
2 should be to maintain safety of principal while maximizing the total
3 return.
4 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34.102A-2 of Title 62, unless
6 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 As used in the Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund Act:
8 1. "Appreciation" means any increase in the value of assets
9 held in the Trust Fund;
10 2. "Board" means the Invest in Oklahoma Board as established in
11 Section 71.1 of Title 62 of the Oklahoma Statute, or its successor;
12 3. "Corpus" means the principal of the Trust Fund;
13 4. "Distributable earnings" means an amount that equals up to
14 four percent (4%) of the immediately preceding five-year average
15 fiscal-year end asset valuation of the Trust Fund, as determined by
16 the Board;
17 5. "Earnings" means all income derived from the investment of
18 monies in the Trust Fund including but not limited to income,
19 earnings, interest, and investment returns;
20 6. "Trust Fund" means the Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund;
21 7. "Interest" means income earned from the investment of funds
22 in interest-bearing instruments, including but not limited to bonds,
23 notes, and other fixed-income securities; and
24
Req. No. 17252 Page 4

1 8. "Initial deposit" means the first transfer of funds into the
2 Trust Fund as provided by law.
3 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
4 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34.102A-3 of Title 62, unless
5 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
6 A. There is hereby created in the State Treasury a trust fund
7 to be known and designated as the "Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund".
8 The members of the Invest in Oklahoma Board shall be considered
9 trustees of the fund. The fund shall be a continuing fund, not
10 subject to fiscal year limitations, and shall consist of all monies
11 directed for deposit to the fund pursuant to legal transfers,
12 apportionments, or appropriations, as well as any interest or
13 investment income derived from such deposits. All monies accruing
14 to the credit of the said fund are hereby appropriated and may be
15 utilized in accordance with the provisions of the Taxpayer Endowment
16 Trust Fund Act.
17 B. Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, all
18 interest and income derived from deposits to the Taxpayer Endowment
19 Trust Fund, shall be credited to the Trust Fund.
20 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34102A-4 of Title 62, unless
22 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. The Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund shall be administered,
24 managed, and overseen by the Invest in Oklahoma Board, with
Req. No. 17252 Page 5

1 admi nistrative assistance provided by the State Treasurer and any
2 other individual or entity designated by the Board. The Board shall
3 invest the assets of the Trust Fund with the care, skill, prudence,
4 and diligence under the circumstances then prevailing that a prudent
5 investor acting in a like capacity and familiar with such matters
6 would use in the conduct of an enterprise of a like character and
7 with like aims. Additionally, the Board shall diversify the
8 investments of the Trust Fund so as to minimize the risk of large
9 losses, unless under the circumstances it is clearly prudent not to
10 do so. The Board may take or delegate all actions reasonably
11 necessary to administer, manage, and protect the Trust Fund but only
12 in a manner that meets the standard provided in this subsection.
13 B. Notwithstanding the provisions of Section 89.2 of Title 62
14 of the Oklahoma Statutes, the Board may invest and reinvest assets
15 of the Trust Fund in any manner not prohibited by law, including but
16 not limited to real property assets, stock, and other equity
17 investments.
18 C. Subject to Board approval, the State Treasurer shall:
19 1. Employ or contract for the services of professional
20 custodians, consultants, and managers of the assets of the Trust
21 Fund, including legal counsel as needed;
22 2. Establish investment and fund management guidelines; and
23 3. Adopt an investment policy.
24
Req. No. 17252 Page 6

1 D. The contracting for services described in paragraph 1 of
2 subsection C of this section shall be exempt from the Oklahoma
3 Central Purchasing Act, but shall be conducted by the State
4 Treasurer under a written process approved by the Board.
5 E. The State Treasurer shall provide administrative support to
6 the Board as needed; provided such support does not exceed that of
7 two (2) full-time equivalent employees employed by the State
8 Treasurer.
9 F. The State Treasurer may seek reimbursement, and the Board
10 may reimburse from Trust Fund assets, the expenses incurred by the
11 State Treasurer's Office for the performance of the duties assigned
12 by this act to the State Treasurer.
13 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34.102A-5 of Title 62, unless
15 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 A. Investments of Taxpayer Endowment Trust Fund assets by the
17 Board shall be made in accordance with written policies developed by
18 the Board. The written investment policies shall prioritize:
19 1. Generating long-term investment income for public purposes;
20 and
21 2. Preserve and protect the Trust Fund's principal while
22 maximizing the Trust Fund's total return;
23
24
Req. No. 17252 Page 7

1 The written investment policies shall be designed to maximize
2 yield within each class of investment instrument, consistent with
3 the safety of the assets invested.
4 B. 1. Not later than July 1, of each year, the Board shall
5 forward a copy of the written investment policy to the Governor, the
6 Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives, the President Pro
7 Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate, and the State Treasurer. The
8 State Treasurer shall maintain one copy of the investment policy in
9 the Office of the State Treasurer for public inspection during
10 regular business hours. Copies of any modifications made by the
11 Board to the investment policy shall be forwarded to the Governor,
12 Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives, the President Pro
13 Tempore of the State Senate, and the State Treasurer;
14 2. Not later than November 1, of each year, the Board through
15 the efforts of the State Treasurer, shall publish an annual report
16 on the State Treasurer's website, including the Trust Fund's
17 financial statements, statements of receipts and disbursements
18 related to trust fund assets and investment activities during the
19 period, relevant market value appraisals of assets, comparisons of
20 Trust Fund performance to internal benchmarks, a summary of
21 investment activity during the period, and any other information the
22 Board deems of interest to the public.
